"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","3. P0 and P1 use an MPC AND protocol (using the AND triple generation described in Ap- pendix A) to compute the correction word cw (ℓ+1) ←  ⃗i∗ 0[ℓ]⊕⃗i∗ 1[ℓ]  ∧(L0 ⊕L1)  ⊕  1⊕⃗i∗ 0[ℓ]⊕⃗i∗ 1[ℓ]  ∧(R0 ⊕R1)  ."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","3. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb selects a random word rb to blind pmb, and the Pb exchange pmb +rb."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","4. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb updates bt′ b ←btb · ((pm1−b + r1−b) + pmb +rb)."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","5. The parties use MPC to compute shares eF0 and eF1 of (F0 +F1)·(pm0 +pm1)."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","6. The parties then compute F ′ 0 ←eF0 +r0 and F ′ 1 ←eF1 + r1 respectively, and exchange them to reconstruct F ′ ← F ′ 0 +F ′ 1."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","","none","5. After running the above protocol, t0 +t1 = ˚t0 ⊕ ˚t1 = eri. Proof. Denote pm = pm0 +pm1. First observe that bt0[i]+ bt1[i] = 0 for i ̸= ri, so pm = bt0[ri] +bt1[ri] = ˚t0[ri] − ˚t1[ri], which is either +1 or −1, and so pm2 is always 1. Also note thatbt0 +bt1 = pm·eri. Let r = r0 +r1, F = F0 +F1, eF = eF0 + eF1. Then bt′ b = btb · (pm + r), so bt′ 0 + bt′ 1 = (pm · eri) · (pm + r) = eri · (1 + pm · r). Also eF = F · pm, and F ′ = eF + r = F · pm + r. Finally, recall that v0 + v1 = −F · eri, so that t0 + t1 = (bt′ 0 +bt′ 1) −(v0 + v1) − (bt0 + bt1) · F ′ = eri · ␀(1+pm·r)+F −pm·F ′ = eri · ((1+pm·r)+F −pm·(F ·pm+r)) = eri. 3924    32nd USENIX Security Symposium USENIX Association"
